f82a6a7d-893a-4761-a722-ad0e76975376.value: This handy Pole of Inconvenience is at the top of a dirt track mountain pass. Why not add it to your collection?

71a1a720-8e24-4c5c-98a2-2b2b52913f77.value:
Nestled amongst the mountains of Kosovo is this wonderful little unassuming pole, suggested by Mr Aaron - a 2022 participant. It was quickly verified by us after we saw the video evidence of how stupid it is.

It's a real beauty. Bring your sturdy underwear.

0f044202-21c5-44cc-bbb9-56d53eea1afe.value: There's two ways to get here. We know one might be possible. The other way? What a wonderful slab of inconvenience.

190f3bc2-7cde-4aa1-9f43-6e4138c3a81b.value: High up, twisty, and not particularly close to anything else that you may merit convenient.

6c5bd204-02ae-469a-af23-163cd0cc0856.value: Romania has some quite resplendent dirt tracks to get your machine stuck in. And here is just such a track.

9c94b99c-7a72-4241-b4c2-d63ac1269a5a.value:
What used to be a typical and collector’s edition ceramic plate beautiful Romanian village is now still a beautiful Romanian village, but buried under 90 metres of industrial waste. It’s a vast toxic lake, flooded with an acidic sludge that’s laced with copper, lead, zinc and arsenic. Don’t forget to pack your swimming costume.

The aptly named ‘Team Toxic Waste’ went there on a little reconnaissance mission on the Pioneers Monkey Run Romania
We asked them for a quote - "It was horrific" – Rich Sawtell. Well that's succinct.

b785cd29-852f-43f5-be5a-e63e0191f176.value: Ah, the end of the tarmac. What better place to slap a Pole than the middle of a Romanian forest on a slab of mud.

23aac737-4732-49c0-92d8-bb61bf4c0f20.value: Formerly known as the "Eagle's Nest," because it’s rather high. It’s a massive ruined ancient city awaiting your trembling legs on a remote mountaintop.

ae6d8fbf-4f21-4aa6-90e1-08a8bcf1f8f0.value: Some random flames that have been burning on a mountainside for thousands of years. Great place to toast a teacake.

bb9fb47e-0ad6-4c66-beec-8ad855cbe69b.value: End of the road in the middle of the mountains. Nice view, if you can make it.

cd484740-4e2b-4496-bb44-ff090c07dde2.value: As roads go this one is grade 1 corker. Steep as shit, winding through the mountains with big old drop offs of doom. This is really one of the best Poles of Inconvenience out there.

8ad99eef-407c-4fca-a642-a752e87250a5.value: An abused and forgotten metropolis, abandoned for centuries. Lovely spot for a nice Earl Grey.

b52e32b9-5208-46cf-a7da-cb2b33d7867f.value: One of the favourite Poles from the 2022 edition, for bloody good reason. It's tough, high as a politician on a weekend in Bogota and a possible car-breaker.

0899c744-27c3-4428-835e-bea2befcb4bb.value:
We couldn’t beat this description by a local guide on Google Maps:

“Mediaeval communal tombs with human bones still visible, sit on a promontory above the gorge: in times of plague, infected villagers would voluntarily enter these tombs and wait for death.”

Sounds perfect.

ca3534d4-d824-48ca-94f2-64b744e37ed9.value: You'll need prayers to get here, and prayers to get away again. Rather fitting, really.

12e981bb-709e-4173-b033-aa469f85a99a.value: Massive ruined communist monument atop a ruddy great hill.

cc7f2e2c-14df-4e9d-a4c7-444980187201.value: To get here, you have to take the highest paved road in the Balkans. The badly-maintained road is potholed, narrow and steep. There are 28 hairpins and no barriers protecting you from the sheer drops. It sounds idyllic.

a64afbe2-5410-4582-a7c6-9979ff84c707.value: High in the southern Alps, this rather inaccessible point is the perfect place to reach if it's a massive detour.

77207c9b-3243-415e-8495-29e91f630277.value: The best place we find for inconvenience is either at a dead end or the middle of a dirt track. This handy little number is the latter.

3962cf46-ef08-46d4-a60b-cb9f81378704.value: Further mountainous track joy to bend your tires.

1e0d671e-71d6-4f3f-a56c-f8ec988bf5c1.value: A super high dirt track pass into the high Atlas. Good luck!

997a2dee-bfd3-449c-8b35-c08d6cd0e2e5.value: A gigantic sandpit for adult children. AKA the Sahara. We've positioned this pole as close to the middle as it might be possible to get.

e4c60cba-dfc6-46bc-a9e0-c7fbb64a4458.value: The start of the longest conveyor belt in the world. So big it can even be seen from space. Thankfully, you won't be in space, you'll be in. a tiny, boiling hot car, cursing us for sending you somewhere so pointless.

bd02d9e3-d717-4671-ae02-3d651e76fa4a.value: What better way to make a difficult journey harder than trying to get 30km off road to the wrong side of a salt flat. You will most likely need sand ladders.

85db3643-731a-4cee-a792-8e08a41550ed.value: Ever-so-slightly inconvenient this one, though that's kind of the point.

51689190-601c-4fa0-887d-90a1137b0fe4.value: Tamanrasset is an old stone hermitage on a remote pass in the Hoggar mountains. You might be forced to have a police escort to get here. Or maybe not.

e08d00b0-d973-4cb7-a775-41e1af91b89e.value: A huge salty flat thing in the Sahara that's also right next door to the Star Wars village. This pole in the centre is where we feel most inconvenience might be found..

ca6ce8ed-0a6a-4cc2-ab6d-d43a68fcec46.value: This won't be the toughest POI to hit, but if you want to snag one that includes a phone box that was once owned by Queen Elizabeth II, then this is probably your best bet.

f883f0cc-293f-49d6-a206-0d843e9c1b00.value: Ever wanted to drive right through a pylon? Of course you have. Well, now thanks to us, you can. You lucky buggers.

13ee11bd-4563-4dc5-afd3-a00ed80d4978.value: Once the highest suspension bridge on the planet, this cheeky little lofty pole is a nice, easy introduction to Algeria. We spoil you sometimes.

cd424bfb-0474-4a7e-b5e2-80bf46b79103.value: Seeing as we love monkey bikes, we thought this would be right up your alley. If you're doing the POI on a monkey bike then you should absolutely do everything in your power to make it here.

712310ed-9f1d-4f04-a799-d3f0f0b77a4a.value: We must be going soft as this POI is located in the middle of a swimming pool. Well sort of, it's a kind of pond. But seeing as you would have driven to the middle of the world's largest sandbox for it, it's probably going to feel pretty bloody good snagging this one.

0d1afdde-fd91-4119-b945-d956af133689.value:
This spot looks like a great place to whip out the stove and make a nice cup of tea. Apparently, the road up to it is "is in dreadful condition and requires strong nerves to negotiate it."

Sounds like you'll need that cuppa.

b529d805-4581-48c6-af8e-de1e4f99abe7.value: We've never pretended to be sophisticated, and we're not going to start now. This pole is where it is for one, simple, immature reason.

95cb3267-5c10-4f24-87fd-e339d8583d20.value: Apparently, the gravel track to get up here is brutal, narrow and steep. It sounds lovely to us.

ee1d8d29-d68e-4261-8252-5b8b4aed2e8d.value: By all accounts, this is the steepest road in all of Italy, with some bits of it reaching a rather engine-warming 30% gradient. Splendid. No prizes for going down it, you have to go up.

63ad7fab-dca3-4b4c-8583-cbff1b21c23f.value: Sadly, the road here is all tarmac but, thankfully, a mere 48 hairpin bends lay between you and this pole. Bring your sick bag.

5b384b11-f8f2-47dc-8d5d-6e3c94258c78.value: The narrowest street on the planet. Now that's a tad inconvenient.

48eb0365-b3cc-4542-916d-6ed91e3e823a.value: The highest motorable road in Europe. Needless to say, it's a bit high, and a bit wiggly. Like Mr Tickle after a heavy dose of amphetamines.

f1990600-e3bc-4af5-932c-2c177f072d01.value: A mile out to sea, you'll have to park and walk here to nab this one. There's even an actual, rusty metal pole waiting for you. You lucky things.

359cb9e1-e8e4-4980-b957-8a02d98ae461.value: The highest point in Latvia at a dizzying...um 312m above sea level.

849341e8-e37c-48a0-ac25-93dde70b4081.value: Nothing here. Just a road. Miles away from anywhere.

5f7e370d-a9ae-43ae-886b-df696cb4934a.value: Bugger all here. Really, bugger all.

2081a0f5-da5d-4d1b-9a0c-fda3fc4211fb.value: As far as you can possibly go in the wrong direction in Europe. And a rather splendid place to find yourself. Unless the weather is terrible. Which it will be.

27fc8762-7c8e-4ac3-afcf-ad397282db7d.value: Europe's most northernly point. Make it here, and you're already 5 degrees into the Arctic Circle.

c85b3edb-7d52-4890-8d54-3fddda377025.value: What better place to visit than one that has been abandoned by all humanity for decades.

3c1dcfa7-d3fb-49dd-9d7f-f87fc8d04287.value: This village is called 'A' and here's a sign to prove it. The road is annoyingly flat, but it's quite the trek to get here.

ae05a0eb-8895-4815-bd25-e9c169c918ab.value: This is the highest public motorable road in all of Sweden. It's also miles from anywhere.

e423b8e1-d243-458c-b3db-b6d13d2a653f.value:
Team Lightning YakQueen reports: "Nice spot. But the what3words square is a little bit off the track. I’m not against danger but the 3x3 square is off the side of a road down a large cliff thing. The road is the goodun tho."

We've shifted the POI so it no longer requires abseiling gear.

This one is courtesy of Kit Monsen a Mongol Rally veteran and bone-fide Norwegian. "Think Cabin in the Woods meets Norwegian Fjord." he said. Ok we said. We're coming.

939ba82e-723a-49d4-b512-29e36dec7a59.value: Discovered in the first Poles of Inconvenience and found to be most excellent.

ceb1cf8d-d360-4ded-ac3e-fac679b41610.value: Here you'll find the geographical centre of Europe - verified by some clever French chaps back in 1989.

7f0aa1e9-5d83-4636-a1b0-b5a2e45f5c8b.value: The most Northernly point of Denmark. No reason whatsoever to go there, so go there you should.

748170f2-c7da-481e-b63b-25df08706e8b.value: Conveniently, or not, to get to this one you have to drive across a tidal road that isn't there half the time. Super.

79320663-3e2d-4d2f-bc57-9baf35bc8b87.value: Behold. The world's largest cheese slicers. Bag this and your life shall be complete.

35403372-8d4b-4146-b921-b0aa62a76893.value: From our highly advanced satellite system (well, zooming in a bit on google maps), it looks like you might be able to get your vehicle here. Maybe.

f883fe68-65c9-40bb-bb18-9ebad44ef752.value: About as far away from anywhere useful as you could possibly want to be.

8c75a9b6-d71a-417c-94a1-c85f4b146690.value: A high and winding mountain pass through the Scottish highland. Perfect for making yourself lost and, likely, wet.

d11b2d26-a6bc-4cc1-ba03-4875e04557d2.value: A handy slab of dirt track on the edge of the lake district.

68d0b45b-92e7-4eae-a4f7-96bdba733f84.value: Because you're probably heading north to south here's a handy pair of poles that will force you to travel East to West. High in the Yorkshire Dales. Hopefully it's raining and muddy as shit for you.

8c1ad995-3fd4-4605-92cb-c1e627e4fbbf.value: One of the most daft tracks in the UK. Totally unsuitable for a small vehicle.

06cd1c78-b0f1-4dca-ba77-a739ab24a83a.value: This being a training ground for the UK military means that sometimes it's closed and being blown up. Try not to get shot by avoiding the red flags. Fun bit of off road though.

1b1d6a4e-ca79-4c29-81cd-d9e5ed8ac397.value: A green lane of some magnificence that also has the advantage of being in Devon which is a stupid place to go to. Unless you live in Devon. In which case this one is far too sensible to count.

1a686756-073f-4d78-b0d3-9a565acf7079.value: We've said it before, and we'll say it again. We never pretended to be mature.
